In this study, the renal-friendly Li-CPDs with the function of promoting peripheral nerve regeneration were prepared by a one-step microwave reaction, using lithium citrate (LC) as the Li+-containing carbonaceous source and urea as the nitrogen dopant, respectively (Fig. 1
                        ). Presumably, the non-lithium portions would undergo a condensation and carbonization process to form CPDs, while the lithium carboxylate moieties would be directly anchored onto the surface of CPDs. As shown in Fig. 2
                        A, the as-synthesized Li-CPDs exhibited a uniform spherical morphology, with an average diameter of 4.52 nm. The lattice fringes of 0.21 nm within carbon cores could be ascribed to the (100) plane of graphite (Fig. 2A inset) [29]. It was observed that the solution of Li-CPDs displayed bright green fluorescence under ultraviolet (UV) light irradiation (Fig. 2C inset). The photoluminescence (PL) spectra of Li-CPDs presented an excitation-dependent feature (Fig. 2B), and the maximum excitation and emission wavelengths were 495 nm and 554 nm, respectively (Fig. 2C). There were three main peaks at 236 nm, 342 nm, and 425 nm appeared in the UV-vis absorption spectra of Li-CPDs, corresponding to the π→π* transition of C=C bonds and the n→π* transitions of functional groups [30].
